{{Quote|I was on an information raid once, back when we were trying to get data on Grand Admiral Makati out of the Boudolayz library&hellip;|Wedge Antilles|<ref name="VotF">''[[Vision of the Future]]''</ref>}}
'''Afsheen Makati''' was a [[Grand Admiral/Legends|Grand Admiral]] in the [[Imperial Navy/Legends|Imperial Navy]] who [[Commander/Legends|commanded]] the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Imperial]] [[Star Destroyer/Legends|Star Destroyer]] [[Steadfast (Imperial-class)/Legends|''Steadfast'']] in the final [[Standard year/Legends|years]] of the [[New Order/Legends|New Order]]. A cryptic group known as [[Prophets of the Dark Side|The Secret Order]] led the Grand Admiral to a [[Alliance to Restore the Republic/Legends|Rebel]] base on the [[Planet/Legends|planet]] [[Thila/Legends|Thila]], where he was attacked by the Order's [[Supreme Prophet]], [[Kadann]], after his [[Executive officer/Legends|first officer]] ridiculed the dress of the Order's members. Makati developed a deep hatred for the Supreme Prophet in the following years. The Grand Admiral escaped the [[Battle of Endor/Legends|destruction]] of the [[Death Star II/Legends|second]] [[Death Star/Legends|Death Star]] and retreated to [[Coruscant/Legends|Coruscant]], swearing his allegiance to whomever controlled [[Galactic City/Legends|Imperial City]]. Makati seemingly received a chance at revenge against Kadann when an [[Rajah Ubooki|impostor]] of the Supreme Prophet claimed the Imperial throne. Believing him to be genuine, Makati tracked down the impostor and trapped him on [[Scardia Station]] with the help of [[Azrakel]], a former apprentice of the real Kadann. The Grand Admiral [[Death/Legends|wiped out]] the rest of the [[Church of the Dark Side|false Prophets]] and killed the impostor in a hail of [[Turbolaser/Legends|turbolaser]] fire. Makati himself died a short [[Time/Legends|time]] later.

==Biography==
{{Quote|Learn to reign in your subordinates, dear Admiral.|Kadann|<ref name="WWGA" />}}
[[File:Kadann-TDSS.png|thumb|left|200px|Kadann, Makati's nemesis]]
Afsheen Makati was a [[Human/Legends|Human]] [[Gender/Legends|male]] and one of twelve members of the [[Imperial Navy/Legends|Imperial Navy]] elevated to the [[Military rank/Legends|rank]] of [[Grand Admiral/Legends|Grand Admiral]] by [[Galactic Emperor/Legends|Emperor]] [[Palpatine/Legends|Palpatine]] during the [[Fete Week|New Year's Fete Week]] ceremony in [[2 BBY/Legends|2 BBY]].<ref name="WWGA" /> Makati's service record was no more distinguished than numerous [[Admiral/Legends|admirals]] in the Imperial Navy and his appointment was considered a surprise by many.<ref name="TEGW">''[[The Essential Guide to Warfare]]''</ref> In the final [[Standard year/Legends|years]] of the [[New Order/Legends|New Order]], Makati [[Commander/Legends|commanded]] the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Imperial]] [[Star Destroyer/Legends|Star Destroyer]] [[Steadfast (Imperial-class)/Legends|''Steadfast'']].<ref name="CSWE">''[[The Complete Star Wars Encyclopedia]]''</ref> During his service to the Empire, a shadowy Imperial group known as [[Prophets of the Dark Side|The Secret Order]] led Makati to a [[Alliance to Restore the Republic/Legends|Rebel]] base on the [[Planet/Legends|planet]] [[Thila/Legends|Thila]]. After Makati's [[Executive officer/Legends|first officer]] made a snide remark about the dress of the Order's members, the Order's leader, [[Supreme Prophet]] [[Kadann]], lashed out at Makati with [[Force lightning/Legends|Force lightning]] and ordered him to control his subordinates,<ref name="WWGA" /> leaving the Grand Admiral badly injured.<ref name="CSWE" /> Makati went on to harbor a great deal of hatred for Kadann after the incident. Along with Grand Admirals [[Nial Declann]], [[Miltin Takel]], and [[Osvald Teshik]], Makati was present on the [[Death Star II/Legends|second]] [[Death Star/Legends|Death Star]] during the [[Battle of Endor/Legends|Battle of Endor]]. He was able to escape the [[Battle station/Legends|battle station]] before it was destroyed by the Alliance and retreated from the ensuing chaos back to [[Coruscant/Legends|Coruscant]].<ref name="WWGA" /> After Palpatine's [[Death/Legends|death]] above Endor, Makati remained loyal to the Empire, continuing to defend his territories while awaiting instructions from whoever succeeded the Emperor.<ref name="TEGW" /> He was the subject of a [[New Republic/Legends|New Republic]] information raid on an Imperial library on [[Boudolayz]] during the nascent government's hunt for the surviving Grand Admirals.<ref name="VotF" />

When [[Rajah Ubooki|Kadann's impostor]] claimed the Imperial throne for himself, Makati believed him to be the real Kadann, and his feelings of hatred resurfaced.<ref name="WWGA" /> Makati refused the impostor's call to return to Coruscant to help him take over the planet<ref name="CSWE" /> and requested permission from [[Director of Imperial Intelligence|Imperial Intelligence Director]] [[Ysanne Isard]], the current head of the Empire in opposition to the impostor, to hunt him down. Makati searched through [[Imperial Intelligence/Legends|Imperial Intelligence]] files and located Kadann's embittered former pupil, [[Azrakel]], who also believed the impostor to be genuine.<ref name="WWGA" /> At Makati's command, Azrakel provided details on the [[Lost City of the Jedi]], where the impostor had been trapped, and [[Scardia Station]], headquarters of the [[Church of the Dark Side|false Prophets]].<ref name="CSWE" /> Using this information, Makati was able to wipe out the false Prophets<ref name="END">{{Hyperspace|url=hyperspace/member/insideronline/88/indexp2.html|text=''Evil Never Dies: The Sith Dynasties''|int=Evil Never Dies: The Sith Dynasties}}</ref> and trap the false Kadann, who had recently escaped the Lost [[City/Legends|City]] with the help of the [[mutant]] [[Triclops]], on Scardia Station. Makati announced his victory over the impostor on the station's [[Comm unit/Legends|comm system]], mocking his sparkling robe. Using every [[Turbolaser/Legends|turbolaser]] at his disposal, Makati [[Bombardment of Scardia Station|destroyed]] the [[Space station/Legends|station]] and killed the impostor, fulfilling his revenge.<ref name="WWGA" /><ref name="CSWE" /> Makati met his own end soon after<ref name="WWGA" /> while fighting to keep the [[Corporate Sector/Legends|Corporate Sector]] in Imperial hands,<ref name="TEGW" /> and was able to gain some measure of true vengeance post-mortem, as Azrakel was later able to [[Mission to Bosthirda (Galactic Civil War)|track down]] and kill the real Kadann on [[Bosthirda/Legends|Bosthirda]].<ref name="END" />

==Personality and traits==
{{Quote|Your 'subordinate' Azrakel was kind enough to help me find you, my Emperor. He doesn't care for your sparkly dress either.|Makati, to Kadann's impostor|<ref name="WWGA" />}}
Rather than turning [[Warlord/Legends|warlord]], as several of his colleagues did, Afsheen Makati remained loyal to whomever controlled [[Galactic City/Legends|Imperial City]] under the banner of the Empire. He was persistent in his vendetta against Kadann and his intense hatred for the Supreme Prophet after the incident at Thila nearly consumed the rest of his life. He began his quest for vengeance once the false Kadann laid claim to the Imperial throne, believing him to be the real Kadann. Makati was relentless in his search for the impostor's whereabouts, and once he located Azrakel, he was ruthless in disposing of the impostor and the other false Prophets, mocking the impostor just as the real Kadann had mocked him on Thila.<ref name="WWGA" />

==Behind the scenes==
{{Quote|Makati's fate was intentionally left ambiguous. Makati was the only other GA besides Thrawn that Tim Zahn had referenced himself, and therefore Dan and I thought it was only fair to allow the inventor of the Grand Admirals tell the tale of Makati taking the Final Jump if he so chose.|Abel G. Peña on the [[StarWars.com]] [[StarWars.com Message Boards|Message Boards]]|<ref name="Abel">{{SWBoards|url=thread.jspa?threadID=169992&start=120#9393638|thread=The other Imperial Grand Admirals&hellip;|user=[[Abel G. Peña|Halagad]]|date=2005-01-26|time=2:18 PM|quote=''Makati's fate was intentionally left ambiguous. Makati was the only other GA besides Thrawn that Tim Zahn had referenced himself, and therefore Dan and I thought it was only fair to allow the inventor of the Grand Admirals tell the tale of Makati taking the Final Jump if he so chose.''}}</ref>}}
Makati was first mentioned in a throwaway line in [[Timothy Zahn]]'s novel, ''[[Vision of the Future]]'', published in [[1998]].<ref name="VotF" /> He was later eventually given a full back-story and a first name in the [[Star Wars Insider 66|''Star Wars Insider'' 66]] article ''[[Who's Who: Imperial Grand Admirals]]'', by [[Abel G. Peña]] and [[Daniel Wallace]].<ref name="WWGA" /> He was given a further expansion in ''[[The Complete Star Wars Encyclopedia]]''.<ref name="CSWE" />

Initially cut from ''Who's Who: Imperial Grand Admirals'', Daniel Wallace indicated that Makati's Star Destroyer was named ''Steadfast'', a [[Starship/Legends|ship]] from the ''[[Star Wars: Crimson Empire]]'' [[Star Wars comic books|comic book]] series.<ref name="Dan">{{JCFCite|url=posts/12041813|board=Authors and Artists|thread=The Official Daniel Wallace Discussion Thread|user=[[Daniel Wallace|Dan Wallace]]|date=2003-06-15|time=7:56 PM|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180330121728/http://boards.theforce.net/threads/the-official-daniel-wallace-discussion-thread.5863946/page-5}}</ref> This was later [[canon]]ized in ''The Complete Star Wars Encyclopedia''.<ref name="CSWE" /> According to Abel G. Peña, the circumstances of Makati's death were deliberately left ambiguous in case Timothy Zahn, who created the character, wished to describe Makati's death himself.<ref name="Abel" />

''Who's Who: Imperial Grand Admirals'' was originally intended to be published in an issue of the ''[[Star Wars Gamer]]'' magazine under the name ''[[Dirty Dozen: The Imperial Grand Admirals]]''. However, the magazine was discontinued, and the article was instead published in ''[[Star Wars Insider]]'', albeit containing less information than the original and lacking any [[roleplaying game]] stats.<ref name="Blog">{{Blog|danwallace|16|Grand Admirals: What Have They Got in their Pocketsses?}}</ref> Makati's entry in the original article was intended to tie in with the fall of the false Kadann, and it identified Makati's subordinate as Commander [[Vivant]] from ''Crimson Empire''. The original article also contained an adventure seed titled "Raid on Boudolayz" that described the New Republic's hunt for Makati, an event that was first referenced in ''Vision of the Future''. Among the cut material was a campaign led by Makati to retake the Corporate Sector;<ref name="DD:TIGA">"[[Dirty Dozen: The Imperial Grand Admirals]]"</ref> this campaign was later mentioned in [[2012]]'s ''[[The Essential Guide to Warfare]]''.<ref name="TEGW" />

{{Cutstart}}
===Cut content===
Makati disciplined Vivant after Kadann punished the Grand Admiral for his subordinate's comment concerning the Secret Order's sparkling regalia, though Makati's disgust at being humiliated in front of his crew remained with him for years. Makati was one of many Grand Admirals targeted by the New Republic after the Empire's fragmentation at Endor. [[Lieutenant/Legends|Lieutenant]] [[Judder Page/Legends|Judder Page]] and Commander [[Wedge Antilles/Legends|Wedge Antilles]] led an information raid on a special information storehouse on Boudolayz in the Corporate Sector to gain data crucial to the Makati campaign. However, Makati was slowly reasserting his control over the Corporate Sector, which the Empire lost a year after Endor. He began his conquest of the Corporate Sector with Boudolayz and entered into conflict with the New Republic forces. When Makati died, he held no regrets, at peace with the knowledge that Imperial City still remained in the Empire's control.<ref name="DD:TIGA" />
{{Cutend}}

